When to use ==
In Java, the == operator is used to compare values of primitive types. This operator compares the value of two objects and returns a boolean value. The result of this operator will be true if the two values are equal. For example:

```java
int x = 10;
int y = 10;

if(x == y) {
    System.out.println("x and y are equal");
} else {
    System.out.println("x and y are not equal");
}

```
In this example, x and y are both equal to 10. The result of the comparison is true because both values are equal.

When not to use ==
In Java, you should not use the == operator when comparing complex types like strings, lists, or arrays. This operator compares the reference of two objects and returns a boolean value. This means that if two objects point to the same memory location, they will be considered equal even though they may have different values. For example:

```java
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = s1;

if(s1 == s2) {
    System.out.println("s1 and s2 are equal");
} else {
    System.out.println("s1 and s2 are not equal");
}

```
In this example, s1 and s2 are both equal to the string value Hello because they point to the same memory location in the heap. However, they may have different values since s1 is a string while s2 is a reference to that same string object in memory. Therefore, using the == operator in this case would lead to an incorrect result. Instead, you should use the equals() method on strings or other classes that support it. For example:

```java
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = s1;

if(s1.equals(s2)) {
    System.out.println("s1 and s2 are equal");
} else {
    System.out.println("s1 and s2 are not equal");
}

```
